":"1570","14 April 1546":"14 April 1546","ABT 1548":"about 1548","1549":"1549","1548":"1548","City, of, London, London, England":"London, England, United Kingdom","Clerkenwell, London, Greater London, England, United Kingdom":"Clerkenwell, London, England, United Kingdom","City of London, London, Greater London, England, United Kingdom":"London, Middlesex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Archbould","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Archibald  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Archibald","meanings":["Scottish and English: from a personal name, <i>Archibald</i>, of Anglo-Norman French and (ultimately) ancient Germanic origin (see   Archambault  ). In the Highlands of Scotland it was taken as an Anglicized equivalent of the Gaelic personal name <i>Gille Easbaig</i> ‘servant of the bishop’ (see   Gillespie  ), probably because of the approximate phonetic similarity between <i>Arch(i)bald</i> and <i>easbaig</i>. Both <i>Archibald</i> and <i>Gillespie</i> are personal names much favored among Clan Campbell.","History: This is the name of a leading Nova Scotia family, taken there by four brothers who emigrated from Londonderry, northern Ireland, in 1750–62."]}]},{"name":"Daniel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name (meaning ‘God is my judge’ in Hebrew), borne by the prophet whose story is told in the Book of Daniel. He was an Israelite slave of the Assyrian king Nebuchadnezzar, who obtained great favour through his skill in interpreting dreams and the ‘writing on the wall’ at the feast held by Nebuchadnezzar's son Belshazzar. His enemies managed to get him cast into a lions' den, but he was saved by God. This was a favourite tale in the Middle Ages, often represented in miracle plays. The name has been perennially popular among English speakers since the 16th century and has been particularly favoured since the 1980s."],"variants":[{"name":"Danyal","meanings":["Fanciful respelling of   Daniel ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":29,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":38,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":49,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705207,"age":65,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":67,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705212,"age":100,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Daniel Archbould was born in 1520, in London, England, United Kingdom. He married Agnes Morfyn on 14 April 1546, in Clerkenwell, London, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in London, Middlesex, England."},"et":{"1520–":"1520–Surnud","1525–Female":"1525–Surnud","1548–1570":"1548–1570","1520–Male":"1520–Surnud","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1525":"1525","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1520":"1520","1585":"1585","1570":"1570","14 April 1546":"14. aprill 1546","ABT 1548":"umbes 1548","1549":"1549","1548":"1548","City, of, London, London, England":"London, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Clerkenwell, London, Greater London, England, United Kingdom":"Clerkenwell, London, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","City of London, London, Greater London, England, United Kingdom":"London, Middlesex, England"},"fi":{"1520–":"1520–Kuollut","1525–Female":"1525–Kuollut","1548–1570":"1548–1570","1520–Male":"1520–Kuollut","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1525":"1525","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1520":"1520","1585":"1585","1570":"1570","14 April 1546":"14. huhtikuuta 1546","ABT 1548":"noin 1548","1549":"1549","1548":"1548","City, of, London, Londo